===Etymology 1===
Late 17th century, unknown origin, possibly {{etyl|cy|en}} {{m|cy|moedrodd}} to worry or bother. Possible alternative from the {{etyl|cy|en}} {{m|cy|meidda||to beg for whey}} or perhaps {{m|cy|meiddio||to dare or venture}}. Bear in mind that the "dd" in Welsh corresponds in sound to the "th" in mither, and English also has [[moider]] and [[moither]].

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|/ˈmaɪðəɹ/|lang=en}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb|mithers|mithering|mithered|mithered}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive|Northern England}} To make an [[unnecessary]] [[fuss]], [[moan]], [[bother]].
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[pester]] or [[irritate]] someone. Usually directed at [[children]].
#: ''Will you stop '''mithering''' me!''

